Final pass: This was missed because the existing finding about ret initialization focused on the unrelated code path, not the specific LED interaction.

Root cause: At lines 132-147:
  int main(void) {
      int ret = 0;
      ...
      #if defined(HAS_LED)
      if (gpio_is_ready_dt(&led)) {
          ret = gpio_pin_configure_dt(&led, GPIO_OUTPUT_ACTIVE);  // line 141
          if (ret < 0) {
              LOG_ERR(...);
          } else {
              led_configured = true;
              led_set(1);
          }
      }
      #endif
      #if defined(CONFIG_USB_DEVICE_STACK)
      ret = usb_enable(NULL);  // line 152

The variable 'ret' is reused between LED initialization and USB initialization. If gpio_pin_configure_dt fails (ret < 0), the error is logged but ret is not reset. However, this doesn't actually affect the USB path because ret is immediately overwritten by usb_enable().

Actually, this is fine - ret is overwritten before use. Let me look for a real bug.
